'''Jane McDougal''' (1824–1862) was [[Spouses of the Governors of California|First Lady of California]], wife of [[John McDougal]], [[Governors of California|Governor]] from 1851 to 1852.
==Life== Jane Palmer was born on 16 May 1824 to Nathan Palmer and Chloe Sackett, in Indiana. She married John McDougal on 13 July 1841. During the [[Gold Rush]] the McDougals and their daughter Sue travelled to California on the maiden voyage of the ''[[SS California (1848)|SS California]]''.
John was unsuccessful at mining, and managed his brother's store in [[Sutterville]]. Jane, dissatisfied with the conditions, returned to Indiana with Sue, leaving on 1 May 1849 once more on the ''SS California''. She travelled by sea to [[Panama]], then overland, via Mexico, and back to Indiana. She returned in 1852, being the only first lady to live outside the state while her husband was governor.
McDougal had five children, Sue, Caroline, Latham, William and Lillie. She [[Death in childbirth|died in childbirth]] in 1862.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Palmer McDougal|url=http://governors.library.ca.gov/firstladies/02-Mcdougal.html|publisher=State of California|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>
