{{Infobox monument |monument_name = Parents of Murdered Children Memorial |native_name = |image = File:Oregon City, Oregon (2018) - 173.jpg |caption = The memorial in 2018 |coordinates = |location = [[Oregon City, Oregon]] |designer = |type = |material = |length = |width = |height = |begin = |complete = 2013 |open = September 2013 |dedicated_to = [[child murder]] victims |map_image = |map_text = |map_width = |relief = |extra = }} The '''Parents of Murdered Children Memorial''', sometimes abbreviated as the '''POMC Memorial''', is a memorial to [[child murder]] victims, located at [[Mountain View Cemetery (Oregon City, Oregon)|Mountain View Cemetery]] in [[Oregon City, Oregon]], in the United States.<ref name=Oregonian>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/oregon-city/index.ssf/2013/09/oregon_city_memorial_honors_ch.html|title=Oregon City memorial honors child murder victims|date=September 23, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2013|work=[[The Oregonian]]}}</ref> The memorial was dedicated in September 2013, becoming the first of its kind in the Pacific Northwest and the eighth in the United States.
==Description== The memorial, located in the northwest corner of Mountain View Cemetery in Oregon City, has been described as a "beautiful place for anyone who has lost a loved one or child due to homicide".<ref name=Oregonian/> It features an Oregon/Washington Memorial Wall, a lighted curved wall that encompasses benches, freestanding basalt columns, a spiral-shaped stone walkway and a waterfall over more stonework. It cost $400,000 in cash and in-kind contributions. The memorial was the first of its kind in the Pacific Northwest and the eighth in the United States at the time of its September 2013 dedication.<ref name=Oregonian/>
==History== [[File:Oregon City, Oregon (2018) - 175.jpg|thumb|right|The memorial in 2018]]
Efforts to construct the memorial were led by Mary Elledge, leader of the [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] area chapter of Parents of Murdered Children (POMC), whose son Rob was murdered.<ref name=Oregonian/>
